com/#website","url":"https://roadtostudy.com","name":"Road to Study - Turkey University Guide for Students","alternateName":"Road to Study in Turkey","publisher":{"@id":"https://roadtostudy.com/#person"},"inLanguage":"en-US"},{"@type":"ImageObject","@id":"https://roadtostudy.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/07/accommodation-internet-and-infrastructure-control-in-turkiye.webp","url":"https://roadtostudy.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/07/accommodation-internet-and-infrastructure-control-in-turkiye.webp","width":"2336","height":"1760","caption":"Accommodation, internet, and infrastructure management in Turkey","inLanguage":"en-US"},{"@type":"WebPage","@id":"https://roadtostudy.com/en/hospitality-internet-and-infrastructure-control/#webpage","url":"https://roadtostudy.com/en/hospitality-internet-and-infrastructure-control/","name":"Hospitality Internet and Infrastructure Control in Turkey","datePublished":"2025-10-20T16:32:03+03:00","dateModified":"2026-03-15T21:50:17+03:00","isPartOf":{"@id":"https://roadtostudy.com/#website"},"primaryImageOfPage":{"@id":"https://roadtostudy.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/07/accommodation-internet-and-infrastructure-control-in-turkiye.webp"},"inLanguage":"en-US"},{"@type":"Person","@id":"https://roadtostudy.com/en/author/murat/","name":"Murat","url":"https://roadtostudy.com/en/author/murat/","image":{"@type":"ImageObject","@id":"https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/9f5b866231ae7aed7a61015846c1f0ab6c5797b065ec200b93c5e9daa87897af?s=96&amp;d=mm&amp;r=g","url":"https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/9f5b866231ae7aed7a61015846c1f0ab6c5797b065ec200b93c5e9daa87897af?s=96&amp;d=mm&amp;r=g","caption":"Murat","inLanguage":"en-US"}},{"@type":"BlogPosting","headline":"Hospitality Internet and Infrastructure Control in Turkey","keywords":"Internet","datePublished":"2025-10-20T16:32:03+03:00","dateModified":"2026-03-15T21:50:17+03:00","articleSection":"Cost of Living and Accommodation","author":{"@id":"https://roadtostudy.com/en/author/murat/","name":"Murat"},"publisher":{"@id":"https://roadtostudy.com/#person"},"description":"Learn about internet and infrastructure checks for accommodations in Türkiye. Learn the essential steps for a hassle-free holiday!","name":"Hospitality Internet and Infrastructure Control in Turkey","@id":"https://roadtostudy.com/en/hospitality-internet-and-infrastructure-control/#richSnippet","isPartOf":{"@id":"https://roadtostudy.com/en/hospitality-internet-and-infrastructure-control/#webpage"},"image":{"@id":"https://roadtostudy.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/07/accommodation-internet-and-infrastructure-control-in-turkiye.webp"},"inLanguage":"en-US","mainEntityOfPage":{"@id":"https://roadtostudy.com/en/hospitality-internet-and-infrastructure-control/#webpage"}}]}]}'), '$.content_html', '<h2 class="wp-block-heading">What are the Internet restrictions in Turkey?</h2>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">Internet restrictions in Turkey are primarily governed by <strong>Law No. 5651</strong> (on the Regulation of Publications on the Internet and Combating Crimes Committed by Means of Such Publications) and its subsequent amendments, which grant authorities significant power to block content and websites.</p>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">Key aspects of internet restrictions include:</p>



<ul class="wp-block-list">
<li><strong>Content Blocking and Removal:</strong> Access to content or entire websites can be blocked based on a court order or, in certain urgent cases, by the Information and Communication Technologies Authority (BTK) President.</li>



<li><strong>&#8220;Catalogue Crimes&#8221; and Other Grounds for Blocking:</strong> Sites can be blocked if they are deemed to contain content related to:
<ul class="wp-block-list">
<li><strong>Catalogue Crimes</strong> such as child sexual abuse, obscenity, promotion of drugs, providing a venue for gambling, and incitement to suicide.</li>



<li><strong>Crimes against Atatürk</strong> (under Law No. 5816).</li>



<li><strong>Violation of Personal Rights</strong> (defamation, slander, infringement of privacy).</li>



<li><strong>Threats to Public Order, National Security, and General Health.</strong></li>
</ul>
</li>



<li><strong>&#8220;Disinformation Law&#8221; (2022):</strong> This law introduced a new criminal offense of <strong>&#8220;publicly disseminating false information&#8221;</strong> intended to cause anxiety or panic, which critics argue is vaguely worded and can be used to suppress government criticism and dissent online.</li>



<li><strong>Social Media Regulation:</strong> Foreign social media platforms with over a million daily users must appoint a <strong>local legal representative</strong> and comply with requests for content removal or user data disclosure. Failure to comply can result in fines and significant <strong>bandwidth reduction (throttling)</strong>, making the platforms unusable.</li>



<li><strong>Temporary Throttling:</strong> Authorities have occasionally restricted or slowed down access to major social media platforms (like Twitter/X, Instagram, and YouTube) during times of national crisis, protests, or significant events (e.g., following terrorist attacks or earthquakes), often citing public order or security concerns.</li>



<li><strong>User Data:</strong> The legal framework mandates service providers to retain traffic data for a specified period and requires social media platforms, under certain conditions, to disclose user data to authorities upon request, raising concerns about user privacy and anonymity.</li>
</ul>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">As a result of these laws, thousands of websites and online content (including news articles, social media posts, and even entire domains like Wikipedia for a period) have been subject to access blocks or removal orders in Turkey.<sup></sup></p>



